Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Remove the @21 Day Aged British Sirloin Steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them to come up to room temperature. Peel the @Potatoes{450%g} and halve lengthways. Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. When hot, add the potatoes cut-side down and cook until golden brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. Crush the @Garlic Clove{1}(gently crushed) to release the flavour (no need to peel) and add it to the pan along with a knob of @butter{knob}. Turn the potatoes to brown on the other side, ~{2-3%minutes}. In a #jug{}, mix the @Water for the Stock{250%ml} and @Chicken Stock Paste{10%g}.

Transfer the potatoes to an #ovenproof dish{} and pour in the chicken stock you just made. Cook on the top shelf of the oven uncovered until they are tender and you can easily slip knife into them, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> Make sure the liquid comes three quarters of the way up the potatoes - if it doesn't, top up the dish with a little more water.

Meanwhile, wipe out the pan that you cooked the potatoes in and return to a high heat with the @Water for the Sauce{300%ml}. When boiling, add the @Wild Mushroom Paste{15%g}, whisk well to combine. Simmer until thick enough to coat the back of a spoon (the consistency of double cream), ~{3-5%minutes}. Add the @Creme Fraiche{75%g} and bring to the boil. Taste, season with @?ground black pepper{} if needed then set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in another large frying pan on medium-high heat. Season the steaks on both sides with @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{}. When hot, add the steaks to the pan. Fry until they are browned, ~{1%minute} on each side.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Lower the heat to medium and cook the steaks for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want them cooked to medium-rare. Add ~{1-2%minutes} extra on each side if you like your steak medium or well done.

> IMPORTANT: The steak is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

When the steak is cooked, transfer it to a #plate{} to rest and cover with #tin foil{}. Return the pan to the medium heat, with a splash of @oil{} if dry. Add the @Chopped Cavolo Nero{100%g} and the @Water{2%tbsp}, cover with a #lid{} or #tin foil{} and cook until tender, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> Discard any tough stalks from the cavolo nero. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Pour any resting juices from the steak into the sauce, mix and reheat until piping hot.

> Add a splash of water to the sauce if it's a bit thick.

Share the fondants between your plates. Cut each steak in half and arrange on the plate. Place the cavolo nero alongside and spoon over the sauce. Enjoy!